      <h1>Academic Publications</h1>

      <div class="publication-box">
        <h2>"Cosmic Society: Language and Economy in Walter Benjamin"</h2>
        <p>Kieran Brown</p>
        <p>
          <em>Angelaki: Journal of Theoretical Humanities</em> (forthcoming)
        </p>
        <p>
          This paper examines the intersection of language and economy in the
          writings of Walter Benjamin.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="publication-box">
        <h2>
          "Faux Apparitions: Angels or Cannibals, Between Coetzee and Defoe"
        </h2>
        <p>Kieran Brown</p>
        <p><em>Critique: Studies in Contemporary Fiction</em> (2024)</p>
        <p>
          This article reexamines the relationship between J.M. Coetzee's
          <em>Foe</em> and Daniel Defoe's <em>Robinson Crusoe</em>.
          <a
            href="https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/metrics/10.1080/00111619.2024.2338829?scroll=top#metrics-views"
            target="_blank"
            >View Here</a
          >
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="publication-box">
        <h2>
          <em
            >Inflationary Modernities: Literature, Culture and Economy after
            1789</em
          >
        </h2>
        <p>Kieran Brown & Wayne Stables <strong>(editors)</strong></p>
        <p><em>Palgrave Macmillan</em> (forthcoming)</p>
        <p>
          Collecting 10 chapters from different authors, this book examines
          inflation from various perspectives outside neo-classical economics.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="publication-box">
        <h2>"Mark of Shame: On the Surface of the Weimar Hyperinflation"</h2>
        <p>Kieran Brown</p>
        <p>In <em>Inflationary Modernities</em> (forthcoming)</p>
        <p>
          This chapter theorises the links between the experience of shame and
          inflation during the Weimar hyperinflation.
        </p>
      </div>

